Statcast Metrics: Analyzing and Predicting San Diego Padres Performance

Celestine Hoang, Jeff Ung, Weihao Lin, Rohun Kulshrestha, Aerin Chiu

Introduction

As the age of information moves along, people are increasingly seeking out the statistics of anything that interests them. For a complex sport like baseball that involves many strategies and variables, fans and analysts are eager to uncover the specific factors that drive the performances of players and the outcomes of every game. Major League Baseball (MLB) provides a useful tool that displays Statcast metrics of the top players such as Launch Angle Sweet-Spot Percentage, Exit Velocity, Batted Ball Event, etc. For example, the leader of the aforementioned stats overall is Aaron Judge, who happens to be the American League MVP in 2024 (MLB, 2024). This EDA will aim to discover the most important of these metrics and develop a model that accurately predicts the game outcomes of the San Diego Padres as well as identify the potential best players. We will be testing different models in order to draw this conclusion and further explore the strengths and limitations of our methodology in the discussion. Understanding and interpreting these advanced metrics is crucial for maintaining a competitive edge as the competition intensifies.

Question

How do Statcast metrics such as average hit speed, barrels, and expected home runs (XHR) influence the home run performance of San Diego Padres players? Can a predictive model based on these metrics accurately identify top-performing players and explain discrepancies between expected and actual home runs?

Objectives

The insights from this study can be applied directly by MLB teams, sports analysts, and player development coaches. Key applications include: 1. Player Development: Training programs can be tailored to improve crucial performance metrics such as barrels and exit velocity helping players maximize their home run potential. 2. In-Game Strategy: Managers can adjust batting lineups and game strategies based on predicted player performance under various conditions. 3. Team Building: Front-office executives can use predictive models to identify undervalued players with high potential based on metrics like expected home runs (xHR) and weighted on-base average (xwOBA) optimizing roster construction while managing salary caps. 4. Performance Benchmarking: Analysts can compare individual player metrics to league averages identifying strengths and areas for improvement and ensuring players are continuously assessed and developed.

The Data

The dataset for this analysis was compiled from Statcast leaderboards and MLB’s Baseball Savant, both of which are authoritative sources for advanced baseball statistics. These datasets offer a comprehensive view of player performance by providing metrics such as Expected Weighted On-Base Average (xwOBA), barrels (a measure of quality contact), exit velocity, and expected slugging percentage. Additionally, data on home runs, including expected home runs and their differences, enhances the ability to evaluate offensive efficiency and overall player impact.

This dataset was specifically curated to align with the research question, focusing on key performance metrics that influence game outcomes. By including data on San Diego Padres players who remained with the team throughout the season, the dataset allows for a precise examination of the factors driving team performance. Its combination of raw statistics and derived metrics creates a robust foundation for understanding how individual contributions affect overall results.

Handle Missing Values

We need to look for missing values in the columns since they can lead to inaccurate or biased analysis if not handled properly. If any missing values are found, we would input the median or mean of that column for that missing value. For instance, missing values in the avg_hr_trot and no_doubter_per columns are replaced with the median.

Convert data types

We ensure that columns like year and player_id which are identifiers rather than numeric quantities are converted to character type across relevant datasets. This conversion standardizes data types for consistency and avoids misinterpretation of these values as numerical data.

all_homeruns <- all_homeruns |>
    mutate(year = as.character(year))  

all_expected_stats <- all_expected_stats |>
    mutate(player_id = as.character(player_id),
           year = as.character(year))

all_exit_velocity <- all_exit_velocity |>
    dplyr::mutate(player_id = as.character(player_id))

sd_homeruns <- sd_homeruns |>
    mutate(year = as.character(year))  

sd_expected_stats <- sd_expected_stats |>
    mutate(player_id = as.character(player_id),
           year = as.character(year))

sd_exit_velocity <- sd_exit_velocity |>
    mutate(player_id = as.character(player_id))

Combine Datasets

We then merge the individual datasets from the sd and all statistics respectively by the player column which ensures that all relevant statistics for each player are brought together. This allows for easier analysis and makes sure all players have data in all categories.

Note: Both all_player_stats and sd_player_stats have the same number of players as the exit_velocity and expected_stats datasets but fewer players than the homeruns dataset. This is because the homeruns dataset includes all players who were recorded in the original data, even if they were transferred to a different team in the 2024 season. While the exit_velocity and expected_stats datasets focus only on players who remained in the same team. Therefore, we are only going to focus on players who stayed in the same team all season.

all_player_stats <- all_homeruns |>
  inner_join(all_expected_stats, by = c("player")) |>
  inner_join(all_exit_velocity, by = c("player"))

sd_player_stats <- sd_homeruns |>
  inner_join(sd_expected_stats, by = c("player")) |>
  inner_join(sd_exit_velocity, by = c("player"))

Create New Metrics

To help with our analysis, we want to create more metrics to compare. The new avg_hit_per_pa column measures the average exit velocity per plate appearance meaning it gives an indication of how hard the player is hitting the ball relative to the number of times they come to bat. The new diff_efficiency column calculates the difference between actual runs, xhr_diff, and expected home runs per plate appearance. If this value is positive, it means the player is outperforming expectations in terms of hitting home runs and vice versa.

all_player_stats <- all_player_stats |>
  mutate(avg_hit_per_pa = avg_hit_speed / pa,
         diff_efficiency = xhr_diff / pa) 

sd_player_stats <- sd_player_stats |>
  mutate(avg_hit_per_pa = avg_hit_speed / pa,
         diff_efficiency = xhr_diff / pa)

Remove duplicates

We remove any duplicate rows from the all_player_stats dataset ensuring that each record is unique and avoiding redundancy in the final analysis.

all_player_stats <- distinct(all_player_stats)

Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)

In this section, we aim to analyze the wrangled data to explore trends, relationships, and outliers in player performance metrics for the San Diego Padres. The goal is to identify the most significant factors influencing player performance and game outcomes using Statcast metrics.

Overview of Metrics

We start by examining summary statistics for critical metrics such as Average Hit Speed, Barrels, Expected Weighted On-Base Average (xwOBA), and Home Run Efficiency. Average hit speed measures the average velocity of batted balls, while barrels represent high-quality contact hits. Expected Weighted On-Base Average combines exit velocity, launch angle, and historical outcomes to estimate player performance. Home Run Efficiency measures the difference between expected home runs (xHR) and actual home runs relative to plate appearances.

The metrics for the San Diego Padres players show that most players average hit speeds above 90 mph, with standout performers reaching up to 92.7 mph. Barrels range significantly, with some players reaching as high as 77, indicating strong quality contact. The xwOBA values suggest consistent above-average performance across the team, with some players exceeding 0.370. Home Run Efficiency highlights key players like Manny Machado and Fernando Tatis Jr., who significantly outperform expected home run metrics.

  rename(avg_exit_velocity = avg_hit_speed)
metrics <- c("barrels", "avg_exit_velocity", "est_woba")
create_density_plot <- function(metric, title) {
  ggplot() +
    geom_density(data = mlb_stats, aes_string(x = metric, fill = "\"MLB\""), alpha = 0.5) +
    geom_density(data = padres_stats, aes_string(x = metric, fill = "\"Padres\""), alpha = 0.5) +
    scale_fill_manual(values = c("MLB" = "#B22222", "Padres" = "gold")) +
    labs(
      title = title,
      x = metric,
      y = "Density",
      fill = "Team"
    ) +
    theme_minimal()
}
density_plots <- list(
  create_density_plot("barrels", "Barrels Comparison: Padres vs. MLB"),
  create_density_plot("avg_exit_velocity", "Average Exit Velocity Comparison: Padres vs. MLB"),

)

Data Analysis

This section presents a comprehensive data analysis of the factors influencing home run performance using Statcast metrics. We employed a combination of analytical techniques including correlation analysis, linear regression, and random forest modeling to explore relationships and predict key performance metrics. The correlation matrix helped identify significant relationships between variables and detect multicollinearity, where two or more features are highly correlated, potentially distorting their individual contributions. To address this, we applied appropriate modeling techniques. We selected two complementary models for predicting home run performance: Linear Regression and Random Forest. We chose Linear Regression for its interpretability and ability to quantify relationships using coefficients and p-values, highlighting statistically significant metrics. Additionally, we applied Random Forest to capture complex, non-linear interactions and reduce overfitting through its ensemble learning approach. Model performance was evaluated using R², RMSE, and MAE, ensuring accurate and reliable predictions of home run totals.

We are calculating the correlation matrix to explore relationships between key performance metrics such as xhr_diff, hr_total, avg_hit_speed, no_doubter_per, and barrels. Data Splitting and Preprocessing

The model evaluation and visualization section provides an assessment of the performance of the predictive models, including key metrics like R² and error analysis, alongside visual aids such as scatterplots and feature importance graphs to illustrate the relationship between input variables and predicted outcomes. These evaluations help ensure that the models are robust and accurately reflect the underlying patterns in the data.

Data Splitting

We decided to split the dataset into 80% training and 20% testing sets to evaluate the model’s performance on unseen data and verify a reliable assessment of its predictive accuracy.

set.seed(123)  
data_split <- initial_split(all_player_stats, prop = 0.8)  # 80% training, 20% testing
train_data <- training(data_split)
test_data <- testing(data_split)
nrow(train_data)  # Number of training samples
## [1] 201
nrow(test_data)   # Number of testing samples
## [1] 51

Data Preprocessing

Before model training, we applied standard preprocessing steps, including centering and scaling numeric features to standardize variable ranges. We also performed correlation filtering to address multicollinearity, ensuring that each feature contributes unique information to the model. This improved model interpretability and reduced potential overfitting.

rec <- recipe(hr_total ~ avg_hit_speed + barrels + no_doubter_per + xhr_diff, data = train_data) |>
  step_center(all_predictors()) |>
  step_scale(all_predictors()) |>
  step_corr(all_predictors(), threshold = 0.9)  

prepped_data <- prep(rec, training = train_data)
train_preprocessed <- bake(prepped_data, new_data = NULL)
test_preprocessed <- bake(prepped_data, new_data = test_data)

Model Performance Evaluation

lm_model <- lm(hr_total ~ avg_hit_speed + barrels + no_doubter_per + xhr_diff, data = train_preprocessed)

Random Forest

We trained a Random Forest model to predict home run totals and assess feature importance using “Mean Decrease in Gini.” This metric measures how much a feature contributes to the accuracy of the Random Forest model by indicating its impact on splitting the data and reducing impurity in decision trees. Features with higher Mean Decrease in Gini values have a stronger influence on the model’s predictions making them more critical for accurate outcomes.

set.seed(123)
rf_model <- randomForest(
  hr_total ~ avg_hit_speed + barrels + no_doubter_per + xhr_diff, 
  data = train_preprocessed, 
  ntree = 500
)
importance_df <- as.data.frame(importance(rf_model))
importance_df$Feature <- rownames(importance_df)
colnames(importance_df) <- c("MeanDecreaseGini", "Feature")
importance_plot <- importance_df |>
  arrange(desc(MeanDecreaseGini)) |>
  ggplot(aes(x = reorder(Feature, MeanDecreaseGini), y = MeanDecreaseGini)) +
  geom_point(color = "blue", size = 4) +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(
    title = "Feature Importance: Random Forest Model",
    x = "Features",
    y = "Mean Decrease in Gini"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()
importance_plot

The Random Forest model identified barrels as the most critical predictor of home run totals, followed by average hit speed, XHR Diff, and no-doubter percentage, as shown in the feature importance graph. The Mean Decrease in Gini highlights the relative contribution of each feature emphasizing that barrels play a significant role in improving the model’s predictive accuracy. Compared to the linear regression model, which explained 93% of the variance in home runs, Random Forest provided greater flexibility in capturing complex relationships as demonstrated in subsequent scatterplots. This underscores the importance of consistent high-quality contact in driving home run performance.

Summary Table

The Model Comparison Table highlights performance metrics for Linear Regression and Random Forest models, comparing their R², RMSE, and MAE values. The Random Forest model slightly outperformed Linear Regression, achieving an R² of 0.95, indicating that 95% of the variance in home run totals was explained by the input metrics. Its lower RMSE (2.42) and MAE (2.10) also confirm its superior predictive accuracy.

# Model Comparison Table
lm_predictions <- test_preprocessed |> 
  mutate(predicted_hr_total = predict(lm_model, newdata = test_preprocessed))

  mutate(predicted_hr_total = predict(rf_model, newdata = test_preprocessed))

Top Predictors of Home Runs Barrels, Average Exit Velocity, XHR Diff
Statistically Significant Metrics Barrels (p < 0.01), XHR Diff (p < 0.01)
Most Impactful Players Fernando Tatis Jr., Juan Soto, Manny Machado
Best Model Performance Random Forest (R² = 0.95, RMSE = 2.42)
Predictive Limitations Model does not account for external factors like weather or injuries

Scatterplot of Actual vs. Predicted Values

The scatterplot shows a strong positive linear relationship between actual and predicted home runs, indicating that the model predicts home run totals accurately. The alignment of points along the black trend line suggests a high degree of correlation and consistency in the model’s predictions.

test_predictions <- test_preprocessed |>
  mutate(predicted_hr_total = predict(rf_model, newdata = test_preprocessed))
ggplot(test_predictions, aes(x = hr_total, y = predicted_hr_total)) +
  geom_point(color = "blue") +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", color = "black", se = TRUE) +
  labs(
    title = "Actual vs. Predicted Home Runs",
    x = "Actual Home Runs",
    y = "Predicted Home Runs"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()

Scatterplot: Barrels vs. Total Home Runs

The scatterplot shows a positive linear relationship between barrels and total home runs suggesting that an increase in barrels correlates with a higher number of home runs.

outliers <- all_player_stats |>
  arrange(desc(hr_total)) |>
  slice(1:5) # Top 5 players with the most home runs
ggplot(all_player_stats, aes(x = barrels, y = hr_total)) +
  geom_point(color = "darkgreen", size = 3) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", color = "black", se = TRUE) +
  geom_text(
    data = outliers, 
    aes(label = player), 
    vjust = -1, hjust = 0.5, color = "blue", size = 4, fontface = "bold"
  ) +
  labs(
    title = "Barrels vs. Total Home Runs",
    x = "Barrels",
    y = "Total Home Runs"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size = 16),
    axis.title = element_text(size = 12),
    axis.text = element_text(size = 10)
  )

Results & Discussion

Some key takeaways from the analysis are that 1) barrels are the most important driving factor in determining performance, significantly outperforming the next best factors (average hit speed and expected home runs) in predictive power using the random forest model. 2) The R^2 value for the linear regression model is 0.93, which means that the model can explain 93% of the variance in home run totals with low error. 3) The model accurately predicts actual home runs. From the two scatterplots directly above, we can see that data points fit tightly around the predicted values. This analysis highlights the Statcast metrics that best produce home runs, includes multiple models to evaluate player performance, achieves a highly predictive model with linear regression, and applies the models across the Padres as well as the entire MLB, ensuring that the relationship between barrels and home runs is consistent. Additionally, barrels emerged as the most significant predictor of home run performance, showing higher predictive power than other key metrics like average hit speed and expected home runs, as assessed by the random forest model. As mentioned in the analysis above, some of the metrics we used could be correlated, which may distort their effects on home runs (multicollinearity). Another limitation in this analysis is that the only metrics considered were those collected by the MLB and not external factors like weather, field irregularities, etc. These factors can potentially influence home run performance significantly. Altogether, we can generally expect the home run performance of San Diego Padres players to be good if we have high barrels and high average hit speed. Teams can use predictive models during player scouting to identify potential high performers based on barrels and exit velocity. Additionally, focusing on improving players’ launch angles could further optimize performance.

Conclusion

In this study, our goal was to use Statcast metrics provided by the MLB to investigate what factors contribute to home run performance. We rigorously explored the relationships between each of the Statcast metrics that we deemed the most significant and built a highly accurate model to estimate total home runs based on these metrics. Our analysis revealed that barrels were the most important metric when predicting total home runs, and we were also able to identify top players for the Padres, such as Manny Machado, Juan Soto, and Fernando Tatis Jr. for expected weight on-base averages. In conclusion, our study shows that improving in areas such as average hit speed and more importantly barrel rates has a high likelihood of improving home run performance for the San Diego Padres players.
